aude. Met Elliot Richardson at a Radcliffe dance: \"he made a pest of himself by constantly cutting in, but she put up with it because he was a superb dancer\" (Washington Post). When Nixon ordered Richardson to fire Archibald Cox: \"There was never any doubt about Elliot's resignation... he knew he had no choice.\" Reading Is Fundamental: joined board 1969; chairwoman 1981-1996. Under her leadership, children served grew from 3M to 3.7M; volunteers from 100,000 to 219,000; federal funding from $7.6M to $13.2M. National Parnassus Award; Helen Homans Gilbert Award (Radcliffe). Also chairwoman, advisory board Second Genesis (DC drug treatment program) from 1978. Washington Post obituary Jul 28, 1999 (Bart Barnes). (Washington Post; Reading Is Fundamental; FindAGrave)","body":"Anne Frances Hazard Richardson was the wife of Elliot Richardson, who resigned as Attorney General rather than fire Watergate prosecutor Archibald Cox in 1973. She was also the longtime chairwoman of Reading Is Fundamental, growing the program from 3M to 3.7M children served.","number":2},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"He was a pest, but he danced","body":"She met Elliot Richardson when he kept cutting in at a Radcliffe dance her senior year — “she put up with it because he was a superb dancer.” Twenty-one years later, when Nixon ordered the Cox firing, “there was never any doubt about Elliot’s resignation.”"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Anne Frances Hazard","first_name":"Anne","last_name":"Hazard","married_names":["Richardson"],"middle_name":"Frances"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST039"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Chairwoman","organization":"Reading Is Fundamental","start_year":1981,"end_year":1996},{"role":"Advisory board chair","organization":"Second Genesis","start_year