822,"date_month":7,"date_day":8,"location_city":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"orbit_connections":[{"name":"Gov. Henry Baldwin Harrison (via Frances Louisa Blake Osborn)","relationship":"Arthur Dimon Osborn — son of US Representative Thomas Burr Osborne, and husband of HD1572 Frances Louisa Blake — had a sister Elizabeth who married Governor Henry Baldwin Harrison of Connecticut","notes":"Frances Louisa Blake (HD1572) married Arthur Dimon Osborn. Arthur's father was US Representative Thomas Burr Osborne (CT). Arthur's sister Elizabeth married Henry Baldwin Harrison, Governor of Connecticut 1885-1887. Their son Thomas Burr Osborn (chemist) and Arthur Sherwood Osborn were grandchildren of Eli Whitney Blake. (Wikipedia on Eli Whitney Blake)","connection_type":"orbit_non_descendant"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{"father_id":"X02815","father_name":"Dr. Elihu Blake","mother_id":"X02816","mother_name":"Elizabeth Fay Whitney Blake"},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["engineering"],"notable_blurb":"Blake stone crusher inventor, nephew of Eli Whitney","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eli_Whitney_Blake","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Patented the Blake stone crusher for road-building","detail":"Blake graduated Yale in 1816 and trained at Litchfield Law School before abandoning law to work at his uncle Eli Whitney's armory in Whitneyville. He also held the first US mortise lock patent (1833, Blake Brothers) and served as president of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences. His son Henry Taylor Blake (HD1568) went on to build New Haven's park system — the stone-crusher's roads and the park commissioner's parks both serving the same expanding American city. (Wikipedia; research_notes)","body":"Eli Whitney Blake patented his stone crusher in 1857. The first commercially successful machine of its kind, it made macadam roads practical on a national scale and is credited as foundational to American infrastructure. He is in the National Inventors Hall of Fame.","number":1},{"number":2,"category":"science","header":"He left law for his uncle’s armory","body":"Litchfield-trained, Blake abandoned the law for Eli Whitney’s armory; his 1833 mortise lock was the first such American patent, and his 1857 stone crusher put him in the National Inventors Hall of Fame. He died at ninety-one."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Eli Whitney Blake","first_name":"Eli","last_name":"Blake","middle_name":"Whitney","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778628286/eliwhitneyblake_hmmnvs.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[{"type":"letter","date":"1830-12-09","title":"1830 letter from George Washington Blake (Boston) to Elihu Blake Jr. (NYC) mentioning Eli Whitney Blake","description":"Stampless letter from G.W. Blake (1803-?, brother) in Boston to Elihu Blake Jr. (1793-1875, brother) at No. 5 Park Place, NYC. Mentions Eli Whitney Blake by name in connection with Mr. W. prescribing 'be married before the first day of next August' for his malady. Also mentions parents Pa (Elihu Blake Sr.) enjoys tolerable health and mother (Elizabeth Fay Whitney) is well; siblings Maria, Elizabeth, Frances, Josiah Whitney, John Adams; uncle Blake; Aunt Whitney in New Haven; the September 1830 boiler explosion on the steamboat United States. Authors not built in JSON per Jalapeño Rule but documented here for family-correspondence record.","url":"https://sparedandshared2.wordpress.com/letters/1830-george-washington-blake-to-elihu-blake-jr/","source":"Spared & Shared 2 archive (sparedandshared2.wordpress.com)"}],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST024","relationship":"alumnus","institution_blurb":"Studied law there before abandoning law for the Whitney Armory."},{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1816"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","dates":"1816"}],"career":[{"role":"Inventor","organization":"Blake Brothers, New Haven"},{"role":"President","organization":"Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences"}],"slug":"eli-blake-1795"},"HD1556":{"id":"HD1556","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1799},"death":{"year":1876},"parents":{"father_id":"X00501","mother_id":"H00981"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00503","children_ids":["HD1565","HD1566","HD1567","HD1568","HD1569","HD1570","HD1571","HD1572","HD1573","HD1574","HD1575","HD1576"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1822,"date_month":7,"date_day":8,"location_city":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"tags":[],"sources":[],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X02815","display_label":"was her father-in-law"},{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X02816","display_label":"was her mother-in-law; Sister of cotton-gin inventor Eli Whitney"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Eliza Maria O'Brien Blake","first_name":"Eliza","last_name":"Blake","married_names":["Blake"],"middle_name":"Maria","maiden_name":"O'Brien"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Lost two children to disease in early 1836","body":"In early 1836 Eliza Maria buried two of her young children within eight weeks — six-year-old Robert Pierrepont (HD1569) on January 17 and two-year-old Eliza Maria (HD1571) on March 13. She gave the name Eliza Maria again to a daughter born five years later (HD1576), passing down the name from the daughter she had lost."}],"slug":"eliza-blake-1799"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}